Creating a personalized online learning platform requires careful consideration of both the architecture and the requirements. Below is an optimal design and architecture for the backend, along with functional and non-functional requirements.

Recommended Design and Architecture
1. Architecture Overview
Microservices Architecture: This design will allow you to develop, deploy, and scale different components independently. Each service can handle a specific aspect of the platform, such as user management, course management, content delivery, and analytics.
2. Key Components
API Gateway: Acts as a single entry point for all client requests, routing them to the appropriate microservices.
User Service: Manages user registration, authentication, and profile management.
Course Service: Handles course creation, updates, retrieval, and deletion.
Content Delivery Service: Manages multimedia content (videos, documents) delivery to users.
Analytics Service: Tracks user engagement and progress, providing insights for personalized learning.
Database: Use a combination of SQL (for structured data) and NoSQL (for unstructured data) databases to store user information, course details, and analytics data.
3. Communication
RESTful APIs: For synchronous communication between services.
Message Queues: For asynchronous tasks, such as sending notifications or processing background jobs.
4. Security
OAuth 2.0 / JWT: For secure user authentication and authorization.
Data Encryption: Protect sensitive data both at rest and in transit.
Functional Requirements
User Management

User registration and login.
Profile management (update personal information, preferences).
Role-based access control (admin, instructor, learner).
Course Management

Create, update, delete courses.
Enroll and unenroll users from courses.
Provide course materials (videos, articles).
Quizzes and assessments.
Personalization

Recommend courses based on user interests and performance.
Track user progress and adapt learning paths.
Analytics

Track user engagement metrics (time spent, completion rates).
Generate reports for users and administrators.
Notifications

Send email/SMS notifications for course updates, reminders, etc.
Non-Functional Requirements
Scalability

The system should handle increased load by scaling horizontally.
Performance

Response time for API requests should be under 200ms.
Content delivery should be optimized for low latency.
Reliability

The system should ensure high availability (99.9% uptime).
Maintainability

Code should be modular and well-documented to facilitate updates and maintenance.
Security

Protect against common vulnerabilities (e.g., SQL injection, XSS).
Implement regular security audits and compliance checks.
Usability

Provide a user-friendly interface for learners and instructors.
By following this architecture and gathering the specified requirements, you will have a solid foundation for building your online learning platform.

Next Steps
Consider creating a detailed project plan that includes timelines, milestones, and resources needed for development.